1ï¸âƒ£ Definition

Proxy Pattern is a structural design pattern in which a proxy object acts as a substitute or placeholder for a real object to control access to it.

ğŸ‘‰ The proxy and the real object share the same interface,
so the client cannot tell the difference between them.

2ï¸âƒ£ Why Proxy Pattern Came

Proxy pattern exists to solve problems like:

Expensive object creation

Heavy resources usage

Security control needed

Remote access

Lazy loading

Access restrictions

3ï¸âƒ£ Core Idea (Simple Line)

Client talks to Proxy,
Proxy talks to Real Object.

4ï¸âƒ£ Types of Proxy Pattern
ğŸ”¹ 1. Virtual Proxy

ğŸ‘‰ Creates object only when needed
( Lazy loading )

ğŸ”¹ 2. Protection Proxy

ğŸ‘‰ Controls access (security / permissions)

ğŸ”¹ 3. Remote Proxy

ğŸ‘‰ Represents object in another system (network / API)

ğŸ”¹ 4. Caching Proxy

ğŸ‘‰ Stores results to improve performance

ğŸ”¹ 5. Logging Proxy

ğŸ‘‰ Logs access and operations

5ï¸âƒ£ Problem Without Proxy
Client â†’ Real Object


âŒ Always heavy load
âŒ No access control
âŒ No caching
âŒ No security
âŒ No monitoring

6ï¸âƒ£ Solution With Proxy
Client â†’ Proxy â†’ Real Object


âœ” Access control
âœ” Lazy loading
âœ” Caching
âœ” Security
âœ” Performance optimization

7ï¸âƒ£ Structure of Proxy Pattern
Components:

Subject (Interface)

Common interface for Proxy & RealObject

RealSubject

Actual object that does real work

Proxy

Controls access to RealSubject

Client

Uses Subject interface

8ï¸âƒ£ Simple Python Example
# Subject Interface
class Image:
    def display(self):
        pass


# Real Subject
class RealImage(Image):
    def __init__(self, filename):
        print("Loading image from disk...")
        self.filename = filename

    def display(self):
        print(f"Displaying {self.filename}")


# Proxy
class ImageProxy(Image):
    def __init__(self, filename):
        self.filename = filename
        self.real_image = None

    def display(self):
        if self.real_image is None:
            self.real_image = RealImage(self.filename)
        self.real_image.display()


# Client
img = ImageProxy("photo.png")
img.display()   # loads + displays
img.display()   # only displays (cached)

9ï¸âƒ£ What Happened Here?

ImageProxy controls creation of RealImage

Real image is created only when needed

This is Virtual Proxy

ğŸ” Real-Life Analogy (Non-Food)
ğŸ¦ Bank Locker System

You cannot directly access the locker.

Process:

You â†’ Bank Counter (Proxy) â†’ Locker Room (Real Object)


The counter:

Checks identity

Controls access

Logs activity

Then allows access

ğŸ‘‰ Counter = Proxy
ğŸ‘‰ Locker = Real Object
ğŸ‘‰ You = Client

10ï¸âƒ£ Proxy vs Decorator vs Adapter (Important)
Pattern	Purpose
Proxy	Control access
Decorator	Add new behavior
Adapter	Convert interface
11ï¸âƒ£ Advantages

Improves performance

Adds security

Enables lazy loading

Controls access

Supports logging & monitoring

Separation of concerns

12ï¸âƒ£ Disadvantages

Extra layer of complexity

Slight performance overhead

More classes

13ï¸âƒ£ When to Use Proxy Pattern

Use Proxy when:

Object creation is expensive

Access needs control

Object is remote

Caching is required

Security is required

14ï¸âƒ£ When NOT to Use

Avoid Proxy when:

Object is lightweight

No access control needed

Simplicity is priority

15ï¸âƒ£ SOLID Principles Followed

âœ… Open-Closed Principle

âœ… Single Responsibility Principle

âœ… Dependency Inversion Principle

